onalism in both Ireland and Turkey in the 20th century - as a foundation to advance a new theory of religious nationalism. By comparing cases, Goalwin emphasizes how modern political actors deploy religious identity as a boundary that differentiates national groups This theory argues that religious nationalism is not a knee-jerk reaction to secular modernization, but a powerful movement developed as a tool that forges new and independent national identities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aChurch and statezIreland. 0aIslam and statezTurkey. 0aNationalismxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aNationalismxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aNationalismzIrelandxReligious aspects. 0aNationalismzTurkeyxReligious aspects. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  abelief, religion, nationalism, nation building, national identity, religious identity, community, Turkey, Ireland, 20th century, twentieth century, secular, secularism, independence, modern, modernization, politics, identity, Catholicism, Catholic Church, Islam.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076647940uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978826526?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978826526423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978826526/original  a978-3-11-076647-9  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK